.Dd March 28, 2026
.Dt FIND 1
.Os Xao
.Sh NAME
.Nm find
.Nd walk a file hierarchy
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.Nm find
.Op Ar path
.Op Fl name Ar pattern
.Op Fl type Ar type
.Op Fl exec Ar command \&\& "{" "}" \&+
.Sh DESCRIPTION
The
.Nm
utility recursively descends the directory hierarchy for each
.Op Ar path , 
applying specified tests and actions to files and directories
found. By default, the top-level directory specified is always
included in the output.

If no
.Op Ar path
is provided, the current directory
.Pq Sq \&.
is used as the default.

.Bl -tag -width ".Fl exec Ar command"
.It Fl name Ar pattern
Match the file name against the
.Ar pattern .
The
.Ar pattern
follows shell globbing rules (like
.Xr fnmatch 3 ) .
For example:
.Ql \&*.c
matches all files ending with
.Ql .c .

.It Fl type Ar type
Select files that match the specified type. The
.Ar type
can be one of the following:
.Bl -tag -width ".Fl type"
.It f
Regular files.
.It d
Directories.
.El

.It Fl exec Ar command \&\& "{" "}" \&+
Execute the given
.Ar command
for each matching file or directory. The
.Ar command
should include
.Sq \&{ }
as a placeholder for the full file path.
The
.Ar command
is executed once for each matching file.
.Pp
The
.Sq + 
indicates that multiple files may be passed to the command.

.Example:
find . -name "*.c" -exec rm {} +
matches all
.Ql .c
files in the current directory and removes them.

.El
.Sh EXAMPLES
.Bd -literal -offset indent
# Find all files in the /
find /

# Find all files matching *.txt
find . -name "*.txt"

# Find all directories in /etc
find /etc -type d

# Find and remove all *.o files
find . -name "*.o" -exec rm {} +
.Ed
.Sh SEE ALSO
.Xr rm 1 ,
.Xr ls 1 ,
.Xr fnmatch 3

